programmeName: Marine Biotoxin Program at the Washington State Department of Health, Office of Environmental and Health and Safety.
occurredBeforeText: PSP closures have occurred throughout South Puget Sound previously.
additionalLocationInfo: There were several recreational shellfish closures in Pierce County due to PSP. The Pierce County PSP closures started in July and were over by October.
toxicityRange: n Pierce County, 2196 micrograms of PSP toxins in blue mussels, 201 micrograms of PSP toxin in pacific oysters, 315 micrograms of PSP toxin in manila clams, 190 micrograms of PSP toxin in varnish clams and 164 micrograms of PSP toxin in butter clam during August and September in Carr Inlet.  Geoduck from Still Harbor tract reached a maximum of 392 micrograms of PSP toxins on 9/15/14.
effectsComments: In 2014, South Puget Sound had one site that recorded over 2000 micrograms of PSP toxin. There were ten geoduck closures and three all species commercial PSP closures in 2014.There were recreational closures in Pierce County from July to October due to PSP toxins. In 2014 there were no ASP or DSP closures in South Puget Sound. PSP in Pierce County - Carr Inlet was closed due to PSP toxins on July. The closure was expanded to include Hale Passage in September. These areas were reopened to all species except butter and varnish clams in October.   Commercial closures - There were three all species commercial closures in Carr Inlet from August until September during 2014.  Geoduck tract closures - Five geoduck tracts had ten closures in South Puget Sound in 2014. They are - Wyckoff Shoal, Wyckoff South, Still Harbor, Redondo and Lisabuella. Winter geoduck closures are most likely not due to new blooms but may be the result of residual toxin from earlier blooms or re-suspension of cysts by divers who dig geoduck and the consumption of those cysts by the clams.
transvectors: PSP- Blue mussels, pacific oysters, manila clams, butter clams, varnish clams and geoduck clams.

programmeName: Marine Biotoxin Program at the Washington State Department of Health, Office of Environmental and Health and Safety.
occurredBeforeText: PSP closures have occurred throughout North Puget Sound previously. In 2014 a new record for DSP toxins was recorded in pacific oysters and littleneck clams.
additionalLocationInfo: Whatcom, Jefferson, and San Juan counties
toxicityRange: In Whatcom County, 183 micrograms of PSP toxin was the maximum in blue mussels at Bellingham Bay on 9/22/14. In San Juan County,  blue mussels reached a maximum of 549 micrograms PSP toxin in Rosario Strait on 9/16/14. In Clallam County, butter clams reached 268 micrograms of PSP toxin on 3/20/14 at the West Straits.    In Clallam County, pacific oysters reached 41 micrograms of DSP toxins on 7/22/13, a new record for this species in WA. Also in Clallam County, blue mussels reached 180 micrograms of DSP toxin  at Sequim Bay in August. In Whatcom County, blue mussels reached 81 micrograms of DSP toxin at Bellingham Bay in July. In San Juan County, blue mussels from Rosario Point reached 27 micrograms of DSP toxin in August.
effectsComments: Most of the inlets of North Puget Sound have had previous PSP closures.  Penn Cove and Holmes Harbor had ASP blooms in 2005.  ASP toxin did not reach the action level of 20ppm in 2014.   DSP toxins exceeded the regulatory standard in Whatcom, San Juan and Clallam Counites in North Puget Sound. North Puget Sound had DSP commercial closures in Sequim and Discovery Bays in 2014.

In Kitsap County, geoduck from Manzanita tract reached a maximum of 566 micrograms of PSP toxins on 10/20/14.

There were no ASP closures in Central Puget Sound during 2014.

additionalLocationInfo: D. ovum cells in varying concentrations from Galveston Bay to Corpus Christi Bay. Aransas Bay had the highest concentrations of both D. ovum  & OA. Cells detected offshore & inshore; offshore bloom stretched to Brazos-Santiago Pass near the Mexico border.
eventBiblio: Lisa Campbell is publishing a paper on the event in the Journal of Phycology. Kathleen Swanson's paper, The 2008 Texas Dinophysis ovum Bloom: Distribution and Toxicity, is being published in Harmful Algae

programmeName: The CICEET-funded Imaging Flow CytoBot first detected D. ovum coming in at Aransas Pass.  IFBC
locationText: Texas coast (Between Galveston Bay and CCB)
additionalLocationInfo: D. ovum cells were found in varying concentrations from Galveston Bay to Corpus Christi Bay.  Aransas Bay had the highest concentrations of both D. ovum cells and okadaic acid.  Celss were detected both offshore and inshore; offshore bloom stretched all the way to Brazos-Santiago Pass near the Mexico border.
additionalDateInfo: 2/14/08 Lisa Campbell notified Meridith Byrd of increasing concentrations of D. ovum being detected by the Imaging Flow CytoBot deployed at Aransas Pass.  Discolored water first seen Sat., 3/1/08 in a Port Aransas marina.  All bays reopened to shellfish harvesting 4/8/08
effectsComments: Shellfish harvesting was prohibited in a total of 10 bays, from Matagorda to Corpus Christi Bay.  No human illnesses were ever reported.  Significant because at the time the toxicity was confirmed a local community was hosting their annual Oysterfest.
transvectors: Dinophysis ovum (originally indentified as D. acuminata).  Shellfish confirmed toxic by the FDA.  No human intoxications.
eventBiblio: Lisa Campbell is publishing a paper on the event in the Journal of Phycology.  Kathleen Swanson's paper, The 2008 Texas Dinophysis ovum Bloom: Distribution and Toxicity, is being published in Harmful Algae.

occurredBeforeText: Since 1987, the first year of confirmed occurrence, the problem has occurred every year, with a break in 1993. This year the most affected areas were Minho estuary, Aveiro Lagoon , Mondego estuary, Obidos Lagoon and Sagres.
assaytype: Mostly mussels ( Mytilus edulis ) from these regions presented DSP toxins, in the case of the mussels from Sagres we could not find DSP toxins by HPLC analysis, but the mice died during the first 24 hours after injection, so the harvest was closed in the region. DSP toxins were determined both by the mouse bioassay and through HPLC.

occurredBeforeText: A few more dubious historical records. A yearly more or less large scale and long lasting phenomenon since 1984 according to mouse biossay. The phenomenon has never been so extensively monitored as since 1992. The problems in 1997 were less than average.
additionalLocationInfo: Dinophysis spp. were recorded all along the Norwegian coast but most numerous along the south coast and at two stations, Sognefjord and Romsdal, at the west coast.
additionalDateInfo: Toxins in mussel were recorded at three stations. At the station, Flödevigen, along the coast of Skagerrak in October, at the station Sognefjord in august and at station Romsdal in May-June.
additionalAlgaeInfo: Causative species: Dinophysis spp., with D.acuminata and D.acuta as the most potent species.
toxicityRange: Toxins recorded above the action level.

occurredBeforeText: A few more dubious historical records. A yearly, more or less large scale and long lasting phenomenon since 1984 according to mouse bioassay. The phenomenon has never been so extensively monitored since 1992.
additionalLocationInfo: Dinophysis spp. were recorded all along the Norwegian coast but most numerous along the south and in the innermost part of the Sognefjord at the west coast.
additionalDateInfo: From March and throughout the year concentrations of some few hundred cells/L or more were recorded at one or another station. Among the Dinophysis spp. Occurring along the Norwegian coast, the species D. acuminata and D. acuta are considered as the most potent for toxicity. The latter has its main season in late summer and early autumn.
additionalAlgaeInfo: Most probably Dinophysis spp., with D. acuminata and D. acuta as the most potent species. The latter has its main season in late summer and early autumn.

occurredBeforeText: A few more dubious historical records. A yearly more or less large scale and long lasting phenomenon since 1984 according to mouse bioassay. The phenomenon was not so extensively monitored before 1992.
additionalLocationInfo: Dinophysis spp. were recorded all along the Norwegian Coast, but most numerous along the South-west Coast.
additionalDateInfo: From March and throughout the year.
additionalAlgaeInfo: Concentrations of some few hundred cells/l or more were recorded at some stations. In September-October even samll patches of reddish water due to mass occurrence of Dinophysis norvegica were seen along the South Coast of Norway.

additionalDateInfo: Start of detection of L. polyedra cells in 07/07/03 and end 08/09/03. This DSP episode due to L. polyedra was overlapped with a DSP episode due to D. acuminata.
